{{Infobox person | name = Alejandro Romay | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = Romay small.jpg | image_size = 250px | alt = | caption = Romay in 1990 | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1927|01|20}} | birth_place = [[San Miguel de Tucumán]], [[Argentina]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2015|06|25|1927|01|20}} | death_place = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline}} --> | nationality = | other_names = ''Zar de la televisión'' | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = | years_active = 1940–1997 | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = | style = | influences = | influenced = | home_town = | salary = | net_worth = | height = | weight = | television = | title = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | movement = | opponents = | boards = [[Canal 9 (Argentina)|Channel 9]] | denomination = | criminal_charge = | criminal_penalty = | criminal_status = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relatives = | callsign = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | footnotes = | box_width = }}
'''Alejandro Romay''' (born '''Alejandro Argentino Saúl''' January 20, 1927 – June 25, 2015) was an [[Argentine]] businessman and media mogul.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.buenosairesherald.com/article/192470/tv-zar-alejandro-romay-dies-at-88|title='TV Zar' Alejandro Romay dies at 88|date=June 25, 2015|publisher=[[Buenos Aires Herald]]|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> He worked for many years at [[Canal 9 (Argentina)|Canal 9]] (known under his management as Canal 9 Libertad), and became known as the "''Czar of television''".
==Biography== [[File:Alejandro romany flia 1960s.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Romay in the 1960s.]] Romay started his career in 1940 as radio host at LV 7 Radio Tucumán, at the Tucumán province. He acquired LV 12 Radio Aconquija in 1945, and two years later he moved to Buenos Aires. He kept working as radio host, but started working as well as a radio, TV and theater producer. He became the largest shareholder of [[Canal 9 (Argentina)|Channel 9]] in 1963, and director of it. He lost the channel when it was nationalized in 1974 and moved to Puerto Rico, where he acquired two radio stations.
Romay returned to Buenos Aires in 1983, when [[Raúl Alfonsín]] took power, and acquired back Channel 9. He created Telearte S.A. to manage its programming, and the channel became Argentina's ratings leader for the rest of the 1980s. The 1990s initially saw his media empire expand: he acquired Radio Belgrano, which had been state-owned, as well as a Buenos Aires cable system (BAC). In addition, he bought a Miami television station, [[WJAN-CD|WJAN]], which later was run by his son Omar Romay. He also owned a theater in Buenos Aires and another one in Madrid.
In 1997, Romay retired and began to sell off his media assets. The radio stations went to [[Grupo CIE]] of Mexico, while Canal 9 Libertad was sold to [[Prime Television]] of Australia<ref>[http://www.lagaceta.com.ar/vernotae.asp?id_nota=245710&titulo=Alejandro Alejandro Romay: “por trabajar demasiado, he descuidado a mis afectos”] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719052522/http://www.lagaceta.com.ar/vernotae.asp?id_nota=245710&titulo=Alejandro |date=2011-07-19 }} {{es icon}}</ref> and [[Grupo Clarín]]'s Multicanal cable systems absorbed BAC. He was awarded an honorary [[Martín Fierro Awards|Martín Fierro Award]] in 2003.
At the time of his death in June 2015, he was writing an autobiography.<ref>[http://www.losandes.com.ar/notas/2005/2/14/estilo-144193.asp Alejandro Romay: una vida con estilo propio] {{es icon}}</ref>
