{{Infobox musical artist | name = İbrahim Tatlıses | background = solo_singer | image = İbrahim_Tatlıses_(cropped).JPG | image_size = | caption = | birth_name = İbrahim Tatlı | alias = Emperor, İbo | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|1|1}} | birth_place = [[Urfa]], [[Turkey]] | genre = [[folk music|Folk]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[Arabesque (Turkish music)|arabesque]], [[pop-folk]] | occupation = Singer, actor, director, writer, producer, businessman | years_active = 1970–present | label = {{ubl| Palandoken Plak (1970–1974) | Studyo Yalcin (1975–1977) | Omer Plak (1978) | Turkuola Plak (1979–1982) | Star Plakcilik (1983–1984) | Bayar Muzik (1985–1986) | Emre Plak (1987–1989) | Kaya Muzik (1990–1991) | Raks Muzik (1992–1998) | Universal Muzik (1999–2001) | Erolkose Muzik (2003–2004) | Idobay Muzik (2005–2010) | Poll Production (2011)}} | associated_acts = | website = {{URL|http://www.tatlises.com.tr}} }} '''İbrahim Tatlıses''' (born January 1, 1952) is a folk singer and former actor of Kurdish origin. Since the 1970s he has been one of the most well-known and successful singers of the pop ''[[Arabesque (Turkish music)|Arabesk]]'' style. Tatlıses has recorded 42 albums, including notable albums such as ''Ayağında Kundura'' and ''Selam Olsun'' and was the host of the highly popular television programme ''İbo Show''. He was also a leading actor that appeared in several dozen films, and also worked in the restaurant and tourism businesses. He survived an [[assassination attempt]] in 2011 after being shot in the head.
==Personal life== İbrahim Tatlı{{sfn|Matthews|2011}} was born in Urfa (Şanlıurfa), in the southeast of Turkey.{{sfn|Matthews|2011}} He is of mixed Arab–Kurdish ancestry.{{sfn|Rough Guides|1999|p=409}}{{sfn|Matthews|2011}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Tatlises rapped for using Kurdistan|url=http://www.kurdpress.com/En/NSite/FullStory/News/?Id=5760|work=kurdpress|date=27 October 2013|accessdate=12 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151121032402/http://www.kurdpress.com/En/NSite/FullStory/News/?Id=5760|archive-date=21 November 2015|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Kurdish languages|Kurdish]] is his [[mother tongue]].<ref name="Çelik1999">{{cite book|author=Yasemin Çelik|title=Contemporary Turkish Foreign Policy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y9PXcwFOLNcC&pg=PA70|year=1999|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-275-96590-7|pages=70–}}</ref> He lost his father during childhood, and did not attend high school.{{sfn|SMN|1997|p=70}} He did not know how to read or write growing up.{{sfn|SMN|1997|p=70}}
===Kurdish issue=== In the 1980s the Turkish government had banned the use of Kurdish; at a concert in Sweden in December 1986, he had sung folk songs in Kurdish and was thus prosecuted for separatist propaganda, but found not guilty in 1987.<ref name="WhitmanFroncek1989">{{cite book|author1=Lois Whitman|author2=Thomas Froncek|title=Paying the Price: Freedom of Expression in Turkey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kvYmkcILrysC&pg=PA102|year=1989|publisher=Human Rights Watch|isbn=978-0-929692-15-9|pages=102–}}</ref> The charge was dismissed after he showed regret.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Lois Whitman|author2=Jeri Laber|title=State of Flux: Human Rights in Turkey : December 1987 Update|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WvTZbetXmGYC&pg=PA93|year=1987|publisher=Human Rights Watch|isbn=978-0-938579-68-7|pages=93–|quote=<!--Ibrahim Tatlises, one of Turkey's most popular singers, was recently charged and tried for using a Kurdish phrase at a concert in Sweden; he could have been sentenced to 24 years. The charges were dismissed after Tatlises indicated his remorse.-->}}</ref> In 1988, he was asked by businessman Mehmet Yilmaz at a cultural festival in Usak to sing a Kurdish folk song, but refused, saying "I am a Kurd, but the laws ban me for singing in Kurdish".<ref name="WhitmanFroncek1989"/><ref>{{cite book|title=Kurdish Times|volume=3-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zc0MAQAAMAAJ|year=1989|publisher=Cultural Survival, Incorporated|page=11|quote=<!--Musicians, too, have come under fire when they touched on the sensitive Kurdish issue in Turkey. Efkan Sesen and Tuncay Akdogan, members of the folk music group Yorum (Commentary), were detained in Ankara in November 1988 for singing Kurdish songs.33 Ibrahim Tatlises, a popular folk singer, was asked at a cultural evening in Usak, Turkey to sing in Kurdish. He declined, declaring: "I am a Kurd, but the laws ban me from singing in Kurdish." He was prosecuted for "separatist ...-->}}</ref> For this, he was indicted on September 19, 1988.<ref name="WhitmanFroncek1989"/>
In 1994 there were evidence that Turkish counter-guerrilla organizations targeted Kurdish businessmen, including Tatlıses, Idris Ozbir, Halis Toprak, and Necdet Ulucan.<ref>{{cite book|title=Daily Report. West Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NN6wQ_D6ulYC|year=1994|publisher=The Service|p=57}}</ref> In 1998 it was reported that Tatlıses offered to be an intermediary between the government and the [[Kurdistan Workers' Party]] (PKK) during the [[Kurdish–Turkish conflict (1978–present)|armed conflict]].He recorded an track album with Iranian kurdish musicians Abdollah Alijani Ardeshir.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Thomas M. Wilson|author2=Hastings Donnan|title=Border Identities: Nation and State at International Frontiers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=StlVS9PufnkC&pg=PA287|date=22 January 1998|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-58745-7|pages=287–}}</ref>
In 2018, he gave public support to the [[Turkish military operation in Afrin]] against the [[People's Protection Units]].<ref>[https://onedio.com/haber/ibrahim-tatlises-ten-recep-tayyip-erdogan-a-ozel-afrin-turkusu-816226 İbrahim Tatlıses'ten Recep Tayyip Erdoğan'a Özel 'Afrin' Türküsü]</ref><ref>[https://f.aa.com.tr/en/culture-and-art/turkish-celebrities-visit-hatay-in-support-of-afrin-operation/1105579 Turkish celebrities visit Hatay in support of Afrin operation]</ref>
===Marriage=== After returning from Germany, Tatlıses married Ayşegül Yıldız on 27 September 2011 in the rehabilitation facility where he was receiving treatment.<ref>{{cite news |last=Eğrı |first=Ramazan |url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/magazin/magazinhatti/18844031.asp |title=İbrahim Tatlıses evlendi |work=[[Hürriyet]] |date=28 September 2011 |accessdate=17 June 2013 |language=Turkish }}</ref>
==Musical career== He sold tapes and sang at weddings and in restaurants until a producer discovered him in 1976.{{sfn|Matthews|2011}} He had adopted ''Tatlıses'' (sweet-voiced) as a stage name.{{sfn|Matthews|2011}}
Tatlıses is regarded the most famous of the [[Arabesque (Turkish music)|Arabesk]] singers.{{sfn|SMN|1997|p=66}} He is known popularly as "İbo".{{sfn|SMN|1997|p=66}}
He recorded an track album with iranian kurdish musicians Abdollah Alijani Ardeshir in 2008.
==Assassination attempts== He was shot in the leg in 1990 and survived an assassination attempt in 1998.
On 14 March 2011, he was attacked and seriously wounded in the head.<ref name=ntvmsnbc>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntvmsnbc.com/id/25192018/|title=Kurşun sıkanlar en az 2 kişi|publisher=ntvmsnbc.com|date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=15 March 2011 |language=Turkish}}</ref><ref name=BBCshot>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-12730390 | work=BBC News | title=Turkish singer İbrahim Tatlises shot in head in attack | date=15 March 2011}}</ref> At 00:30 local time, he and his spokeswoman Buket Çakıcı were shot at by unknown assailants after leaving the offices of the private Turkish channel [[Beyaz TV]] following his weekly television show.<ref name=ntvmsnbc/><ref name=BBCshot/> As they entered their vehicle, Tatlises was hit with a bullet that entered the back of his skull and exited through the front. Çakıcı was also hit in the neck, but survived the attack. The perpetrators carried [[AK-47|Kalashnikov]] rifles and escaped in a black car.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.trend.az/regions/met/turkey/1844612.html |title=Famous Turkish singer Ibrahim Tatlises headshot (UPDATE) |date=14 March 2011 |work=Trend |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> He was taken to the Acıbadem Hospital in Istanbul for emergency treatment.<ref name="internethaber">{{cite web |url=http://www.internethaber.com/iste-ibrahim-tatlisesin-son-durumu-334455h.htm |title=Haber: Maslak Acıbadem Hastanesi Başhekimi Çağlar Çuhadaroğlu yoğun bakımda olan İbrahim Tatlıses'in son durumunu açıkladı. haberi|publisher=Internethaber.com |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=17 June 2013 |language=Turkish}}</ref> He underwent a four-hour operation to have the bullet removed, after which he was in stable condition. He regained consciousness five days later.{{sfn|Matthews|2011}} After a week, the doctors announced that he was recovering well. Turkey's Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan visited him and also announced that he was recovering well. The police in Turkey arrested around 20 people involved in the attack.{{sfn|Matthews|2011}} On April 7, Tatlıses left Acıbadem Hospital with a police escort and travelled to [[Atatürk International Airport]], where he was boarded the Ministry of Health's Hawker 900XP air ambulance for Germany, to receive intensive rehabilitation at the Murnau Trauma Clinic.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tatlises arrives in Germany |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/n.php?n=press-scanner--hurriyet-2011-04-07 |work=[[Hürriyet Daily News]] |date=7 April 2011 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>
==Business== Tatlıses is involved in the restaurant and tourism businesses, as well as in construction projects with business partner Ali Sariyildiz in [[Iraq]].<ref name=CNNSHOT>{{cite news |last=Comert |first=Yesim |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/europe/03/14/turkey.singer.shot/ |title=Turkish singer in critical condition after shooting |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref>
